RUNNING NIC HDL SIMULATION

source /var/services/homes/mkpatel/vivado-2017.1.sh
cd /var/services/homes/mkpatel/NIC/sim_nic/sume_mb_minimal_sim2.sim/sim_1/behav/
./simulate.sh &

*** or ***

run through vivado

=====

NIC and PCIE BRIDGE IPs
/var/services/homes/mkpatel/FPGA_IP

=====

RUNNING E1000 QEMU

cd /var/services/homes/mkpatel/RC_QEMU/qemu-e1000-lockstep/build
./10g_launch e1000 &

=====

RUNNING FPGA-NIC QEMU

cd /var/services/homes/mkpatel/RC_QEMU/qemu-e1000-lockstep/build
./10g_launch 10g &

=====

In QEMU monitor the command `hdl_lockstep on` will turn on lockstep mode. `hdl_lockstep off` will turn off lockstep mode. 

QEMU details:
user- mrunal
pass- hello123

To test: 
On e1000 VM:
    sudo ifconfig ens3 up
    sudo ifconfig ens3 1.2.3.5
    nc -v -l 8888 > /dev/null
    *** go to qemu monitor and turn on hdl_lockstep ***

On fpga-nic VM:
    cd nic_driver
    sudo insmod nf10.ko
    sudo ifconfig nf0 up
    sudo ifconfig nf0 1.2.3.4
    *** type the following command but before hitting enter, turn on hdl_lockstep ***
    dd if=/dev/zero bs=1024K count=512 | nc -v 1.2.3.5 8888

Notes: 

Both QEMU VMs create tap interfaces on brdummy bridge.
